Two rounds of severe storms moved across southeast Minnesota on April 12th. The first round occurred in the afternoon as storms producing large hail moved across the area. Quarter sized hail fell from north of Racine (Mower County) east to near Winona (Winona County). A second round of severe storms occurred in the evening. An EF2 tornado moved through Taopi (Mower County), where homes were destroyed or severely damaged, grain bins were destroyed, cars were tossed or rolled, and trees and power lines were downed. Two people sustained injuries while sheltering from the storm when they became trapped under debris. An EF1 tornado occurred just southwest of Spring Valley (Fillmore County), damaging several farm outbuildings and trees. Two EF0 tornadoes occurred southwest of Lewiston (Winona County), where the damage was mainly to trees and one farm. The Mower County Board of Commissioners ratified an emergency declaration for Taopi and a state of emergency was declared for Fillmore County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A half dozen campers were tipped over at a campground northeast of Preston.

An EF1 tornado occurred just southwest of Spring Valley (Fillmore County), damaging several farm outbuildings and trees. Two EF0 tornadoes occurred southwest of Lewiston (Winona County), where the damage was mainly to trees and one farm. The Mower County Board of Commissioners ratified an emergency declaration for Taopi and a state of emergency was declared for Fillmore County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Outbuildings were damaged along with trees and power lines blown down southwest of Lewiston. Parts of the downed trees landed on a house.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large upper ridge prevailed across the region from mid-June through the end of the month resulting in very hot and humid conditions across the Mid-South. The heat was most intense on June 12th and 13th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Remnants of a mesoscale convective system moved across the northern portions of the Mid-South. This produced an outflow boundary that moved south into north Mississippi. It was the focus for severe thunderstorms that produced large hail and damaging wind.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Measured hail of 1 inch fell north of Pickwick Dam.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Remnant outflow boundaries from the previous day's storms resulted in scattered convective development. A moist and unstable atmosphere combined with the previous day's rainfall created a perfect opportunity for showers and strong thunderstorms with hail, damaging wind, and flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flash flooding reported on US-412 and on Buttercup Lane in Paragould.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cluster/line of thunderstorms moved across southern Wisconsin the evening of March 5th.  Within this line of storms, some briefly intense downburst winds occurred across portions of south central to east central Wisconsin.  A brief tornado also occurred in southeast Dane county.  Quite a bit of structural damage was noted to a number of farming sheds and buildings in areas of Dane, Rock and Fond du Lac counties. Heavy rainfall on a frozen ground also led to some basement flooding and minor street flooding.|A home was struck by lightning in the Town of Deerfield.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The tornado path started to the southeast of the town of Dunkirk in Dane County.  This tornado went through a farm and destroyed a tobacco barn, part of a silo and peeled back sheet metal on a few buildings on the grounds.  This sheet metal was noted to have been lofted to locations nearly a mile away.  A few other structures had structural damage to them along the path.

CZ_NAME: ALTAMAHA SD TO FERNANDINA BEACH FL OUT 20NM
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The upper ridge pattern started to break down enabling an influx of deeper moisture (PWAT 2 inches) from the southwest into the afternoon. Isolated strong to severe storms developed where sea breezes and outflows merged near and east of the I-95 corridor, then storms moved offshore of the Atlantic coast.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The ASOS at KSSI measured a peak wind gust of 47 mph.

CZ_NAME: FERNANDINA BEACH TO ST AUGUSTINE FL OUT 20NM
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A front was stalled near the FL-GA state line. SW steering flow pushed a stronger west coast sea breeze front inland through the day, with further enhancement as the sea breezes merged near the St. Johns River basin in the afternoon and evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust of 43 mph was measured by the mesonet station 1695W FSWN CITYSTAUG.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A derecho developed in south central South Dakota and traveled northeast into eastern and northeastern South Dakota. This thunderstorm complex generated 14 total tornadoes across northeastern South Dakota in addition to a broad area of straight-line wind damage with measured speeds up to 102 mph in Gary, SD. The damage swath was so large from this system that it encompassed most of northeastern South Dakota and western Minnesota, with damage to a countless number of homes and trees. The most impactful tornado was an EF-2 which damaged numerous homes in the town of Castlewood and drew national media attention. Governor Kristi Noem requested a Presidential Disaster Declaration, which was later granted, and signed Executive Order 2022-06 to help residents recover from related storm damage. Estimated statewide damage to public infrastructure is assessed at 6.7 million dollars across 20 counties and two reservations. South Dakota National Guard activated personnel to help with clear debris and provide security for the town of Castlewood during cleanup.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter reported estimated 70 mph wind gusts and tree damage.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold air outbreak resulted in low temperatures between -20�� and -10�� December 22 and 23. On Thursday Dec 23, most ground stations in the area did not observe a high temperature above 0��. Strong wind gusts were observed all 3 days with the strongest gusts occurring on Dec 23. Peak wind gusts were between 30-50 mph. The coldest wind chills observed were between -51�� and -30��. The city of Omaha did not observe a wind chill temperature warmer than -19�� on the 23rd.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Interpolation of ground stations near the area had Stanton County mostly below -30�� wind chills for approximately 37 hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong storm system moving through the deep south. A line of thunderstorms developed ahead of this system and moved eastward. Ahead of the line, a very warm, moist and unstable environment developed which along with strong vertical shear, set the stage for an outbreak of severe thunderstorms across parts of southern United States. This event produced 3 tornadoes in southwest Alabama along with wind damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Measured by a Weatherflow station.

A weak area of low surface low pressure formed along a frontal boundary that was draped across the local area. Aloft, shortwave impulses traversed with the better dynamic |forcing over southeast GA. The entire airmass was primed (PWAT over 2 inches) and prevailing westerly steering flow focused the strongest convection along the sea breezes mergers toward the I-95 corridor in the afternoon and into the evening. A cluster of storms formed along the front across NE FL and Duval county. When these slow moving storms encountered the east coast sea breeze as it moved inland, very heavy rainfall rates produced local flooding across portions of downtown Jacksonville, including the Hogans Creek basin near UF Shands.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Power lines were blown down from thunderstorm winds just south of Ponte Vedra Beach.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level trough progressed through the Rockies and into the Central and Southern Plains during the day on November 4th, enhancing strong surface low development over the Upper Red River Valley into Oklahoma. This produced a strong pressure gradient over the Southern Plains and Lower Mississippi Valley, allowing for very rich Gulf moisture to surge north across the Ark-La-Tex area into Eastern Oklahoma and much of Arkansas. This generated moderate instability across these areas during the afternoon, as temperatures rose into the lower to mid 80s. Very strong wind shear was also in place over these areas, with the upper trough reinforcing a cold front southeast into Southeast Oklahoma, Western Arkansas, and East Texas. This trough enhanced large scale forcing along the front, with discrete supercell development also occurring ahead of the main line of storms over portions of East Texas, Southeast Oklahoma, and Southwest Arkansas. Multiple tornadoes, some strong, touched down across these areas, with additional instances of damaging winds also reported before the line of storms overtook these discrete supercells and shifted east across the remainder of East Texas, Southwest Arkansas, and into North Louisiana during the evening and overnight hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: This is the continuation of the Red River County Texas EF-4 tornado. This tornado had weakened upon entering Southern McCurtain County Oklahoma, producing EF-2 damage in rural areas southwest of Idabel, ripping the roofs off of several single family homes. Shortly before entering Idabel, the outer edge of this tornado hit the Oklahoma Mesonet observing platform located about 5 miles to the southwest off of Ravens Nest Road. An anemometer located 10 meters above the platform measured a wind gust of 108 mph, with a nearby single family home sustaining roof damage where EF-2 winds estimated near 125 mph removed a large section of the roof structure with a wall collapsing on another single family home off of Osprey Road. The tornado continued on to snap several hundred trees before hitting a single family home off of Boss Road which had a wall collapse and partial roof damage that could not be rated due to trees falling into the home. More EF-2 damage was observed as the tornado approached Highway 259 when the tornado removed the roof and much of the second story off of a single family home. The two people in the home took shelter on the first floor under the stairs, preventing injury as winds estimated at 125 mph damaged the home. As the tornado moved northeast across Stone Haven Road, a Davis weather station recorded a gust of approximately 130 mph. ||Upon entering Idabel, the tornado damaged additional roofs of homes in several neighborhoods on the southeast side of town. One of the most hard hit subdivisions was Country Club Estates. None of the homes in the Country Club Estates were rated due to tree damage which resulted in much of the structural damage from trees falling into homes. Nearby at the Idabel Country Club, nearly every tree sustained damage on approximately six holes, with mostly snaps observed. There was also some debarking of trees in this area, where an EF-3 swath of damage had begun. Behind the golf course, a single family home was destroyed with most of its walls collapsed except for a small interior room. ||The tornado continued to move northeast, hitting the Kiamichi Family Medical Center where EF-2 damage (near 115 mph) was estimated due to the facade components that were torn from the structure. As the tornado approached Highway 259 and East Washington Street, it damaged the sign of a McDonald's and a swath of EF-3 winds completely destroyed the Donut Crossing and Express Tire stores. A sign from the Donut Crossing store was lofted by the tornado and carried 14.3 miles where it was found on the west side of Eagletown. After crossing East Washington Street, the tornado completely destroyed the Trinity Baptist Church. Winds at this location were estimated to be near 155 mph with the total destruction of the metal building system which was surrounded by a brick wall that collapsed with concrete anchors pulled up from the ground. The tornado moved on to produce narrow EF-2 damage in the more broader EF-1 damage swath with small vorticies likely extending down to the ground from the elevated large funnel cloud at this point. ||After moving northeast of Idabel, the tornado crossed mainly rural areas and completely destroyed chicken houses while snapping hardwood and softwood trees for approximately the next ten miles. An areal survey indicates that the tornado briefly lifted near the Little River and then touched down again in a forested area before damaging a metal structure atop a chicken plant off of Craig Road. A survey team from the National Weather Service Little Rock office found EF-2 damage with 135 mph winds between Eagletown and Broken Bow just south of Highway 70, where numerous trees and several wooden utility poles were snapped near the base near the Tyson Craig Feed Mill, a large elevator structure on top of a silo collapsed with a portion of a metal roof and walls ripped off of an adjacent metal building, and a doublewide manufactured home at the eastern end of Box Turtle Road was thrown off of its concrete pad, nearly pulling out an underground shelter, rolling over it, and landing about 30 feet to the north. Over half of the house was stripped of the undercarriage. Only about one-third of the walls/roof were left with the remainder of the structure removed and scattered well to the north. ||As the tornado crossed Highway 70 just west of Eagletown, many additional pines and hardwoods were snapped and uprooted. Nearly all utility poles within the path were also snapped or pushed over. The tornado then moved into a heavily forested area north of Eagletown with more specific damage noted from Old Winship Road to Pero Creek through the use of high-resolution satellite imagery before the tornado finally lifted a few miles before reaching the border with Northwestern Sevier County in Southwest Arkansas. ||Remarkedly, only 6 injuries and no fatalities were reported from this long track tornado throughout Southern and Eastern McCurtain County Oklahoma. In total, 220 homes were estimated to had been affected by this tornado, with 10-20 businesses damaged or destroyed. Of the total homes affected, 65 of them were destroyed.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An anomalous moisture plume and arctic airmass brought several feet of snow to northwest Montana. Elsewhere, moderate snow produced slick travel along the Interstate 90 and US-93 corridors.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow, along with blowing and drifting snow, caused very tough driving conditions across the area. Total snowfall amounts include: 22 inches Bull Lake, 12 to 18 inches Libby and Eureka, 7 to 10 inches in both Yaak and Trout Creek. Snow bands brought periods of moderate to heavy snow to US-93 between Olney and Whitefish during the evening of Dec. 1.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Multiple locations reported a combination of brief heavy rain, flooding, or debris flows.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A COOP Observer from Moorman Ranch reported 24-hour rainfall at his location of 2.94 inches. He added between 16 and 1800LT a portion of his mountain/hillside came down due to the heavy rain, and he had to clear/repair his driveway with his excavator. Some additional details of note; of the 2.94 inches that fell that Friday, 0.54 inches fell between 2000 that evening and 0400LT the next morning. It was the most rain our observer has seen in a 24-hour period in his 30 years in the area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A complex winter storm brought a mixture of rain, sleet and freezing rain to most of the region, with snow in the mountains, on Sunday January 16th. The mixed precipitation changed to snow from west to east during the late afternoon into the evening and the snow fell heavily at times overnight and early Monday morning. As the parent storm system moved to our northeast, the snow became more showery in nature into Monday afternoon, with snow showers lingering in the mountains through Tuesday morning.||While the heaviest snow occurred in the West Virginia mountains, with 12 to 18 inches reported, another swath of heavy snow occurred up the Ohio River Valley region of West Virginia, where 6 to 10 inches occurred. For the rest of the state, generally 4 to 8 inches fell. The snow began wet and heavy, which caused power outages where the heaviest snow fell. Over 25,000 West Virginians were without power Monday morning.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: During the afternoon hours of August 3rd, numerous thunderstorms developed across parts of eastern Missouri and west-central Illinois, triggered by strong surface heating ahead of a surging outflow boundary. These storms developed within a strongly unstable environment, featuring MLCAPE values ranging from 2500 to as much as 4000 J/kg and largely driven by the very warm and humid boundary layer. The initial round of storms struggled to become organized. Eventually cold pool interactions drove upscale growth into a more linear complex. Damaging winds, occasional large hail were reported as well as bursts of very heavy rain rates. By the evening of August 3rd, storms grew upscale, with additional rounds of thunderstorms developing upstream from this initial activity. The primary hazard transitioned from a damaging wind threat to a heavy rain and flash flooding threat, as storms were extremely efficient rain producers. Warm cloud depths were around 4.5km, along with anomalously high precipitable water values of 2 to 2.5 inches, and Corfidi vector orientations that supported westward back-building which enhanced the potential for locally heavy rain, both in terms of instantaneous rates (2+ inches per hour at times) and training of storms. By mid morning on August 4th, widespread rainfall amounts of 1 to 3 inches fell, mainly along and south of I-70 in Missouri and along and east of I-55 in Illinois. Over the St. Louis metro area, as well as Fredericktown, MO, between 4 and 7 inches of rain fell. There were numerous reports of flash flooding in these areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Up to 3.5 inches of rain fell in a short amount of time across the northern portions of Monroe County causing flash flooding. Numerous roads were flooded.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak area of low surface low pressure formed along a frontal boundary that was draped across the local area. Aloft, shortwave impulses traversed with the better dynamic |forcing over southeast GA. The entire airmass was primed (PWAT over 2 inches) and prevailing westerly steering flow focused the strongest convection along the sea breezes mergers toward the I-95 corridor in the afternoon and into the evening. A cluster of storms formed along the front across NE FL and Duval county. When these slow moving storms encountered the east coast sea breeze as it moved inland, very heavy rainfall rates produced local flooding across portions of downtown Jacksonville, including the Hogans Creek basin near UF Shands.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A personal weather station KFLGLENS19 measured 2.77 inches of rainfall between around 1:45 pm and 4:30 pm.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered to numerous thunderstorms developed in the early afternoon hours across southern and southeastern Georgia. These thunderstorms developed in the vicinity of a nearby front and eventually evolved into a line of thunderstorms as they progressed eastward through the late afternoon hours. The thunderstorms produced numerous reports of severe weather across southeast Georgia, the majority of which were damaging wind gusts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter reported a tree down near the intersection of Old Register Way and Bohler Rimes Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep upper trough rotated through the lower Great Lakes with successive short wave troughs running through the amplified upper level flow. This brought a period of prolonged snows to the area with embedded heavier elements that were enhanced by lake effect and upslope snow processes. Snow accumulations were highly elevation dependent, and due to the orientation of the cold air over the area, this meant that areas in the higher terrain east of Lake Erie were the epicenter of heavy snowfall. Selected accumulations included 11.5 inches in Forestville, 11 inches in Cherry Creek, 13 inches in South Dayton, 10.3 inches in Colden, and 11.5 inches in East Concord.
Scattered thunderstorms developed over the North Carolina foothills during the late afternoon and evening. One of the storms produced hail in Burke County.
A line of thunderstorms moved southeast across western North Carolina during the evening. Several of the embedded storms produced locally damaging wind gusts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Public reported multiple trees blown down in the Kings Creek community.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An unphased low pressure system advanced from south to north through New England. Snow pushed northward to the west of it through all of New York State. Most all areas saw modest accumulations, however in the higher terrain of western New York, accumulations were heavier. The system snow was supplemented by light lake effect as the low pressure system advanced northward and colder air wrapped into the area. Because of the evolution of the system and the incoming cold air, heavy snow amounts were almost exclusively in the higher terrain east of Lake Erie. Selected snow totals included 7.5 inches in Hamburg, 8.3 inches in Mayville, 13 inches in Warsaw, and 10.4 inches in Franklinville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong ridge of high pressure built in across the Southwest heading into the middle part of June, bringing excessive heat conditions to the region. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Favorable monsoonal conditions promoted the development of severe thunderstorms across the region on the 18th. Abundant moisture (PWATs of 1.7-2.0) and instability (MUCAPE 1,000-2,000 J/kg) was in place across south-central and southwest Arizona, while increased easterly steering flow from an upper level low over northern Mexico aided in thunderstorms propagating off the high terrain. DCAPE were around 1,000-1,200 J/kg which helped in allowing strong to severe thunderstorms to produce damaging winds from downbursts. Thunderstorms initially developed along the Mogollon Rim during the early afternoon hours before pushing into the lower deserts of south-central and southwest Arizona through the evening. No injuries were reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Dense blowing dust resulted in visibility dropping below 1/4 mile near I-8 and Fortuna Road. No accidents or injuries were reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A derecho developed in south central South Dakota and traveled northeast into eastern and northeastern South Dakota. This thunderstorm complex generated 14 total tornadoes across northeastern South Dakota in addition to a broad area of straight-line wind damage with measured speeds up to 102 mph in Gary, SD. The damage swath was so large from this system that it encompassed most of northeastern South Dakota and western Minnesota, with damage to a countless number of homes and trees. The most impactful tornado was an EF-2 which damaged numerous homes in the town of Castlewood and drew national media attention. Governor Kristi Noem requested a Presidential Disaster Declaration, which was later granted, and signed Executive Order 2022-06 to help residents recover from related storm damage. Estimated statewide damage to public infrastructure is assessed at 6.7 million dollars across 20 counties and two reservations. South Dakota National Guard activated personnel to help with clear debris and provide security for the town of Castlewood during cleanup.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and power lines were downed by strong wind gusts estimated at upwards of 80 mph. The nearby Watertown Airport weather station reported a peak wind of 76 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An early onset to the Southwest Monsoon brought above normal precipitation to the area, especially mountain locations where some areas received over 2 inches more precipitation than normal. Exceptional(D4) drought conditions were removed from all areas of southern New Mexico.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The month started with Exceptional(D4) drought across the north with Moderate(D1) drought over the southeast.  Conditions across the north improved to Extreme(D3) drought over the north with continued Moderate(D1) drought at the end of June. The Deming Airport reported 1.35 inches of precipitation which was 0.80 inches above normal.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A shortwave trough moving eastward from the eastern Great Lakes, triggered strong thunderstorms in New York state, which moved into southern New England overnight.  The atmosphere was very unstable and surface dewpoints were near 70 degrees. The result was strong to locally severe thunderstorms before daybreak in southeast MA.  Sunshine boosted temperatures in the afternoon, then a cold front swept through in the evening hours, triggering a second round of strong to severe thunderstorms, mainly in western and central MA.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: In Marlboro, a tree was down on power lines on State Street, per the fire department. |Report relayed by amateur radio.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A potent low-pressure system impacted the region during the afternoon and evening hours of May 30th. A larger scale Derecho tracked from far southeastern South Dakota, through much of western through northcentral Minnesota. Widespread damage was reported from damaging winds, and tornadoes. Hail up to 1.5 inches was reported as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several large pine and poplar trees were snapped or uprooted along Highway 72, between Shooks and Kelliher. Time estimated based on radar and nearby wind sensor reports.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A derecho developed in south central South Dakota and traveled northeast into eastern and northeastern South Dakota. This thunderstorm complex generated 14 total tornadoes across northeastern South Dakota in addition to a broad area of straight-line wind damage with measured speeds up to 102 mph in Gary, SD. The damage swath was so large from this system that it encompassed most of northeastern South Dakota and western Minnesota, with damage to a countless number of homes and trees. The most impactful tornado was an EF-2 which damaged numerous homes in the town of Castlewood and drew national media attention. Governor Kristi Noem requested a Presidential Disaster Declaration, which was later granted, and signed Executive Order 2022-06 to help residents recover from related storm damage. Estimated statewide damage to public infrastructure is assessed at 6.7 million dollars across 20 counties and two reservations. South Dakota National Guard activated personnel to help with clear debris and provide security for the town of Castlewood during cleanup.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong synoptic cyclone swinging into the Northern Plains set the stage for a late Spring severe weather outbreak on May 30th. Discrete and semi-discrete supercells developed during the afternoon ahead of an arcing cold front and a nearby surface low. These storms quickly traveled northeast while gradually growing upscale into bowing line segments as storms merged together and new cells formed. During this time, hail and tornadoes occurred; the strongest being an EF2 through Forada, MN. The bowing line segments became dominant and a wind event unfolded.||Strong and broad synoptic lift, little capping, and questionable mid-level shear likely allowed for upscale growth. This caused storm interactions and competing updrafts which may have limited mesocyclone longevity and strength. While property was damaged, no lives were lost on the last day of a holiday weekend when many people were outdoors camping or doing other recreational activities.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tornado developed in far northern Todd County and hit two farmsteads before exiting into Wadena County (see corresponding entry from NWS Grand Forks). At the first farmstead, a garage door was blown in and part of the garage roof came off. Maximum winds for the Todd County portion were estimated to be 90 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A frontal system tracking east across the Bering Sea at the tail end of October reached the Southwest Alaska as a new low developed along the boundary between November 1st and 2nd and strengthened up until moving ashore near the Kuskokwim Delta.  This system brought a multitude of impacts to portions of the region as it headed inland, ranging from minor coastal flooding due to strong onshore winds in portions of Bristol Bay to periods of significant falling and blowing snow, again predominantly focused near the coastline.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tug operator moving a fuel barge reported that westerly winds produced a storm surge of 2 to 3 ft along western Kuskokwim Bay near Quinhagak overnight between 11/1 and 11/2. The combination of surge and moving ice was made it difficult to navigate that part of the bay.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A frontal system tracking east across the Bering Sea at the tail end of October reached the Southwest Alaska as a new low developed along the boundary between November 1st and 2nd and strengthened up until moving ashore near the Kuskokwim Delta.  This system brought a multitude of impacts to portions of the region as it headed inland, ranging from minor coastal flooding due to strong onshore winds in portions of Bristol Bay to periods of significant falling and blowing snow, again predominantly focused near the coastline.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Kipnuk Police Department reported early afternoon arrival of snow and winds with gusts up to 30 kts (35 mph) on 11/1 along with about 2 inches of new snowfall overnight.  The Kipnuk AWOS reported similar conditions during the evening of 11/1 with moderate snow and visibility down to 1/2 mile at times.  Visibility as low as 1/4 mile and moderate snow were also reported at around 6 PM AKST by the Bethel Police Department.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A front associated with a low moving into Southwest Alaska pushed across the western Gulf as a new center formed at the frontal triple point and shifted east-northeast along the north Gulf Coast between November 1st and November 2nd.  Snowfall with significant variability in intensity and accumulation pushed across parts of Southcentral Alaska north of the low, with the highest amounts concentrated over the Susitna Valley and along parts of the Richardson Highway near Thompson Pass, where strong winds also caused significant blowing and drifting of snow as it fell.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow and blowing snow were observed along portions of the Richardson Highway during the overnight of 11/1 into the morning of 11/2.  The Alaska Department of Transportation reported Road conditions through Thompson Pass as difficult to travel due to blowing and drifting snow. Low visibilities with blowing and drifting snow were reported along the Richardson Hwy from Keystone Canyon through Thompson Pass.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system moving into Southwest Alaska from the Bering Sea, sending a layer of warm air aloft overtop sub-freezing surface temperatures. This resulted in a light mix of sleet, snow and freezing rain for a number of locations across the Kuskokwim Delta and Bristol Bay area.  Accumulating ice was minimal for this event.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An employee at the NWS WSO in Bethel reported a mix of freezing rain and ice pellets falling at around 7 AM on the morning of November 30th.  Several AWOS sensors nearby also reported several instances of unknown precipitation from around the same time.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A frontal system tracking east across the Bering Sea at the tail end of October reached the Southwest Alaska as a new low developed along the boundary between November 1st and 2nd and strengthened up until moving ashore near the Kuskokwim Delta.  This system brought a multitude of impacts to portions of the region as it headed inland, ranging from minor coastal flooding due to strong onshore winds in portions of Bristol Bay to periods of significant falling and blowing snow, again predominantly focused near the coastline.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Periods of blowing snow and snow were reported at a number of AWOS sites across mainly the western half of Bristol Bay, with the worst conditions progressing from west to east between the afternoon of November 1st into the evening and overnight hours. Dillingham Police reported that wind and snow began around Noon AKST 11/1 with visibility dropping to 1/4 mile or less at times and total snowfall of up to 4 to 6 inches per a report via Dillingham radio.  Winds Gusted pretty hard, but no damage was reported.  The Dillingham AWOS also reported 1/2 mile snow with wind gusts near 30 mph around 2 PM AKST 11/1.  Nearby AWOS sites reported similar or worse conditions as the heaviest snowfall and strongest winds moved past, including Platinum, Koliganek, Manokotak and Iguigig.  Much stronger gusts were observed at some of these sites, including a gust up to 50 kts or 57 mph at Platinum at 11 AM AKST 11/1.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A front associated with a low moving into Southwest Alaska pushed across the western Gulf as a new center formed at the frontal triple point and shifted east-northeast along the north Gulf Coast between November 1st and November 2nd.  Snowfall with significant variability in intensity and accumulation pushed across parts of Southcentral Alaska north of the low, with the highest amounts concentrated over the Susitna Valley and along parts of the Richardson Highway near Thompson Pass, where strong winds also caused significant blowing and drifting of snow as it fell.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snowfall fell over the Susitna Valley from the evening of November 1st into November 2nd.  Reports from public and spotters for storm total snowfall were up to a foot or more, including a report of 17 inches recorded near Skwentna, 12 inches in Yentna and 8.6 inches near Amber Lake.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak system brought in a warm nose overrunning a cold layer near the surface across Southcentral, with weak large scale lift generating periods of freezing rain/drizzle across parts of the region on November 20th.  Ice accumulations were very minor for this precipitation event, largely due to temperatures warming above freezing as the day progressed and the very light precipitation intensity.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Talkeetna ASOS reported periods of light freezing rain during the afternoon of 11/20.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very potent frontal system progressed across the eastern Bering on the evening of 11/6 into the morning of 11/7, sending a surge of deep, strong southerly flow into the Alaska Peninsula.  The highest wind gusts occurred at higher elevations and where strong southerly flow funneled through gaps in terrain, with peak gusts pushing above 80 mph in a couple locations.  Warm air advection was strong enough to turn most falling precipitation along the front over to rain, even farther north and east along coastal portions of Bristol Bay.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: South-southeast winds came up ahead of a strong, storm force front higher than expected in Port Heiden. Stronger winds (65-75 mph gusts) began right around Midnight AKST on the evening of 11/6 at the Port Heiden AWOS, then picked up into High Wind Warning levels by about 2:30 AM AKST.  Strong winds lasted a remarkable amount of time, with gusts hitting near/above warning criteria for about 9 hours, or from 12 AM to 9 AM AKST 11/7.  The strongest gust recorded of 86 mph occurred at 8:20 AM AKST 11/7.  Local terrain enhancement from gaps in the Aleutian Range south of Port Heiden likely played a role in this event.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak system brought in a warm nose overrunning a cold layer near the surface across Southcentral, with weak large scale lift generating periods of freezing rain/drizzle across parts of the region on November 20th.  Ice accumulations were very minor for this precipitation event, largely due to temperatures warming above freezing as the day progressed and the very light precipitation intensity.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Periods of light freezing rain/drizzle were reported during the early afternoon of 11/20 at both the PANC and PAED ASOS.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper trough moving south within already strong northerly flow helped support strong, gusty winds out of gaps and passes along the north Gulf Coast near Prince William Sound between November 28th and 29th, namely through Thompson Pass.  Similarly strong winds occurred with nearly the same setup with strong northerly flow again late on the 30th into the morning on December 1st.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: On Nov 29, the highest measured wind gust was 66 mph at the PAVD ASOS.|The Thompson Pass Department of Transportation reported that winds were definitely gusting to at least 70 mph in Thompson Pass, and about 60 mph in town between the evening of November 28th and the morning of November 29th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak system brought in a warm nose overrunning a cold layer near the surface across Southcentral, with weak large scale lift generating periods of freezing rain/drizzle across parts of the region on November 20th.  Ice accumulations were very minor for this precipitation event, largely due to temperatures warming above freezing as the day progressed and the very light precipitation intensity.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A mix of freezing rain and snow was reported at the PAEN ASOS near midday 11/20.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system moved east-southeast starting over the eastern Bering, then crossed the Alaska Peninsula and passed just south of Kodiak Island between November 26th and 27th.  This system and its front were able to interact favorably with much colder air in place near and north of the low as it tracked east, with deep frontal lift and seasonably high moisture contributing to efficient precipitation production and a short but intense duration of snow shifting from Bristol Bay to Kodiak Island.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A public report was received at about 12 PM November 27th estimating 9 inches of new snowfall.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system moved east-southeast starting over the eastern Bering, then crossed the Alaska Peninsula and passed just south of Kodiak Island between November 26th and 27th.  This system and its front were able to interact favorably with much colder air in place near and north of the low as it tracked east, with deep frontal lift and seasonably high moisture contributing to efficient precipitation production and a short but intense duration of snow shifting from Bristol Bay to Kodiak Island.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow began falling around 11:15 PM on Nov 27 in Kodiak City.  A spotter reported 7.5 inches of snow at 8 AM November 28th, with around 12 inches total for the snowfall event. Another report was received of 8.25 inches of snow just before 12 PM. A school bus got stuck on a side street near Kodiak City during the same morning. Many additional snowfall reports across Kodiak Island were reported during the course of the day on November 28th, with the highest amounts near 12 inches.  A car accident involving 8 vehicles also occurred where heavy snow was a contributing factor in Kodiak City.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper trough moving south within already strong northerly flow helped support strong, gusty winds out of gaps and passes along the north Gulf Coast near Prince William Sound between November 28th and 29th, namely through Thompson Pass.  Similarly strong winds occurred with nearly the same setup with strong northerly flow again late on the 30th into the morning on December 1st.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A report from the Thompson Pass Department of Transportation confirmed 70mph estimated gusts through Thompson Pass between the evening of November 30th into the morning of December 1st.  A gust to 69 mph was also recorded at the PAVD ASOS.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: In the aftermath of a large, impactful storm system that moved across the region on April 22-23, 2022, a tight pressure gradient resulted in isolated non-thunderstorm high winds across portions of southeast South Dakota during April 24, 2022.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sustained winds reached 40 to 45 mph most consistently during the early morning hours, with a peak wind gust of 61 mph at the South Dakota Road Weather Information System at the Platte-Winner Bridge (station SD554).

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Under a classic setup for storm motion from the Northern Arizona high terrain to Southern Arizona lower deserts, with the monsoon 500mb high positioned over Nevada and Utah, a few multicell storm clusters developed and progressed west-southwest through the lower deserts in the afternoon and evening hours of the 2nd. Increased east-northeast steering flow resulted in relatively high shear values for the monsoon (Sfc-6km shear around 25-30 kts) and very steep mid-level lapse rate (8-8.5 C/km) supported the organized multicellular storm mode with robust updrafts. Inversely, very high DCAPE values, up to 1500-1800 J/kg, supported very strong downbursts. Moisture levels were also above normal which, in combination with the strong updrafts, supported high rainfall rates (1.5-2 inches per hour average). There were a few multicell clusters that moved through Southern Arizona. One through the southeast parts of the greater Phoenix area, another that developed in Yavapai County before descending southwest along US-60 in Maricopa and La Paz Counties, and a third that developed off the Kofa Wilderness terrain south of Quartzsite before being caught by the cluster descending along US-60. Each cluster produced damaging winds, dense blowing dust, small to severe hail, and localized flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Near zero visibility reported at the Phoenix-Mesa Gateway Airport in blowing dust from thunderstorm outflow. No accidents or injuries were reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong ridge of high pressure over the western CONUS resulted in excessive heat conditions across the Phoenix area for the end of August. Temperatures at Phoenix Sky Harbor topped out at 111 degrees on the 30th, while low temperatures near 90 degrees provided little overnight relief from the heat. Above normal temperatures continued into the start of September. According to the Maricopa County Department of Public Health, 9 heat-associated fatalities occurred during this event.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two direct fatalities were reported by the Maricopa County Department of Public Health, with their details, such as age, gender, circumstances, and exact location unavailable.

An anomalously strong ridge of high pressure over the Desert Southwest persisted into the latter part of July, leading to temperatures in excess of 110 degrees in Phoenix most days during this time. Temperatures during this time period peaked on the 22nd with Phoenix Sky Harbor recording a high of 114 degrees. Overnight temperatures provided little relief from the heat as morning lows remained in the 90s for several days. On the 22nd, the morning low temperature only cooled down to 95 degrees in Phoenix. According to the Maricopa County Department of Public Health, 81 heat-associated fatalities occurred during this time.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A thunderstorm wind gust of 58 mph was measured by South Dakota Road Weather Information System site SD589 2 miles east of Dixon.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered thunderstorms developed with a strengthening low-level jet during the overnight hours. With MUCAPE of around 1000 J/kg and 30 knots of effective shear, isolated storms produced up to quarter size hail and damaging wind.

A weak synoptic-scale wave progressed through the area atop a flat upper-level ridge, initiating several clusters of thunderstorms during the afternoon and early evening.  Storms developed near a weak convergence zone, in an environment of 1000-2000 J/kg MLCAPE and marginally strong deep-layer shear of 30 knots.  Mainly multi-cell clusters resulted in marginally severe damaging wind gusts due to sub-cloud dryness and marginally large hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Four large metal grain bins were destroyed by thunderstorm wind gusts, but each of the damaged bins were empty at the time.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered thunderstorms developed in the early morning hours of April 23, 2022 within an area of elevated instability mainly along and east of Interstate 29. A couple thunderstorms produced marginally severe hail.

Scattered thunderstorms developed in the early morning hours of April 23, 2022 within an area of elevated instability mainly along and east of Interstate 29. A couple thunderstorms produced marginally severe hail and damaging wind gusts.

Thunderstorms developed toward midnight on leading elevated warm advection across south central South Dakota and progressed rapidly northeast through areas north of Interstate 90.  Large amounts of DCAPE in the air mass resulted in spotty damaging wind.  A second cluster of storms developed on the tail end of the initial storms on the nose of an increasing low-level jet, using up to 2000 J/kg of elevated instability to rapidly become severe.  Very large hail resulted as storms first developed supercellular characteristics, and then a mix of hail and damaging wind as short bowing segments evolved moving into northwest Iowa and southwest Minnesota.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail was mostly nickel size, with a few stones as large as ping-pong balls.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Another 1 to 1.5 inches of rainfall on May 30 in northeast and east central South Dakota brought back minor flooding to upper portions of the Big Sioux River.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An average of 1 to 1.5 inches of rainfall on May 30 across northeast and east central South Dakota resulted in a return to minor flood stage for the Big Sioux River near Estelline (gage site BSES2).  A crest of 0.21 feet above flood stage was reached late on May 31. Small tracts of agricultural land succumbed to minor flooding. Minor flooding continued at the end of the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stationary front extended from west to east along the I-20 corridor of East Texas and North Louisiana around daybreak on April 17th, which slowly lifted back north into Northeast Texas and Southern Arkansas through the afternoon. Meanwhile, an upper level trough dove southeast through the Southern Plains during the day, reinforcing a cold front southeast across the region. These features enhanced large scale ascent as they interacted with a warm, moist, and unstable air mass that had begun to surge back to the north. As a result, scattered showers and thunderstorms developed and spread east-northeast from late morning through the afternoon across Northeast Texas, Southwest Arkansas, and North Louisiana. An isolated severe thunderstorm developed over Titus County Texas, producing large hail near the Winfield community before shifting off to the east into Southwest Arkansas and North Louisiana through the afternoon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ping pong ball size hail fell just northeast of the Winfield community on Highway 67.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stationary front extended from west to east along the I-20 corridor of East Texas and North Louisiana around daybreak on April 17th, which slowly lifted back north into Northeast Texas and Southern Arkansas through the afternoon. Meanwhile, an upper level trough dove southeast through the Southern Plains during the day, reinforcing a cold front southeast across the region. These features enhanced large scale ascent as they interacted with a warm, moist, and unstable air mass that had begun to surge back to the north. As a result, scattered showers and thunderstorms developed and spread east-northeast from late morning through the afternoon across Northeast Texas, Southwest Arkansas, and North Louisiana. An isolated severe thunderstorm developed a couple miles northeast of Ruston in Southeast Lincoln Parish, producing large hail before weakening as it moved into Northern Jackson and Western Ouachita Parish.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail on the northeast side of Ruston.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A broad upper trough extended south from Southern Minnesota into the Ozarks during the afternoon of April 24th, with a secondary shortwave trough swinging southeast over Eastern Colorado and Western Kansas, which entered Oklahoma during the evening hours. A cold front moved slowly southeast across Northwest Arkansas, Southeast Oklahoma, into Northern and West-central Texas during the afternoon, with large scale forcing ahead of this second shortwave trough focusing showers and thunderstorms along the frontal zone where daytime heating resulted in increased instability over Southeast Oklahoma. Thus, strong to severe thunderstorms developed as a result, which moved across portions of McCurtain County downing trees and power lines and also producing large hail before exiting the area by mid-evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Power lines were downed near Pine Creek Lake.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large upper trough dug through the Southern Plains during the afternoon and overnight hours on April 12th-13th, allowing the dry line to mix east into Central Texas. Large scale forcing increased along the dry line across Central Texas during the late afternoon through the evening, as these storms tapped moderate instability and increasing wind shear ahead of this system. In fact, isolated showers and a few thunderstorms developed during the mid and late afternoon across portions of Northeast Louisiana, with one storm spawning a brief tornado over Northeast Ouachita Parish near the Swartz community. These storms over Central Texas eventually developed in a quasi-linear convection system (QLCS), as they became severe and accelerated east across much of East Texas and North Louisiana during the evening through the early morning hours of the 12th-13th. Instances of damaging winds were reported from these storms, downing numerous trees and power lines, and even spawning isolated tornadoes as well. While these storms exited the region prior to daybreak on the 13th, additional showers and thunderstorms developed along the associated cold front across East Texas during the mid and late morning of the 13th, before spreading into North Louisiana during the peak heating of the afternoon. Thus, adequate instability developed such that some of these storms again became severe, producing instances of damaging winds over portions of North Louisiana and an isolated tornado over Eastern Winn/Western Caldwell Parishes. These storms finally exited North Louisiana during the late afternoon hours of the 13th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were blown down in Olla. An antenna was blown down at a substation in town.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow moving low moved through the region over July 3 through July 5. It carried ample moisture and instability to produce several rounds of thunderstorms and heavy rains. The thunderstorms produced hail, high winds, and lightning. The heavy rains created flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A thunderstorm brought heavy rain and pea size hail. Most of the rain was over in 15 minutes.

A cold front moved slowly southeast across Northwest Arkansas, Southeast Oklahoma, into Northern and West-central Texas during the afternoon, with large scale forcing ahead of this second shortwave trough focusing showers and thunderstorms along the frontal zone where daytime heating resulted in increased instability over Southeast Oklahoma. Thus, strong to severe thunderstorms developed as a result, which moved across portions of McCurtain County downing trees and power lines and also producing large hail before exiting the area by mid-evening.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A coastal storm moved northward from the mid-Atlantic coast late on the 18th to interior New England during the pre-dawn morning hours on the 19th.  Locally heavy rainfall helped bring down damaging wind gusts from a low-level jet across Rhode Island and southeast Massachusetts.  The storm system also brought 1 to 4 inches of snow to the east slopes of the Berkshires in northwest Massachusetts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: In Falmouth at 615 AM EDT (515 AM EST), a trained spotter reported a gust to 57 mph. In Chatham at 513 AM EST, the ASOS at the Chatham Airport (KCQX) recorded a gust to 56 mph. In Provincetown at 522 AM EST, the AWOS at the Provincetown Airport recorded at gust to 56 mph.  In Barnstable at 229 AM EST, the Fire Dept. reported wires down on Main Street.  In Orleans at 354 AM EST, police reported a large limb down on Route 6A.  In Sandwich, between 447 AM EST and 500 AM EST, law enforcement reported a large tree down on Service Road at Tarragon Drive and a tree down on Great Hilll Road near Popple Bottom Road.  In Brewster at 504 AM EST, the Fire Dept. reported a tree down on a detached garage on Gages Way.  In Dennis at 514 AM EST, law enforcement reported a large branch down on Old Chatham Road at Kelley Way.  In Falmouth at 523 AM EST, police reported a large tree down on a house's service wires, but no street name was given.  All of the aforementioned reports were relayed by amateur radio operators.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A coastal storm moved northward from the mid-Atlantic coast late on the 18th to interior New England during the pre-dawn morning hours on the 19th.  Locally heavy rainfall helped bring down damaging wind gusts from a low-level jet across Rhode Island and southeast Massachusetts.  The storm system also brought 1 to 4 inches of snow to the east slopes of the Berkshires in northwest Massachusetts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Winds generally were gusting to 55 to 60 mph.  In Mattapoisett at 526 AM EDT (426 AM EST), a tree was down on wires on Old Brandt Island Road, per law enforcement relayed by amateur radio.  In Rochester at 626 AM EDT (526 AM EST), amateur radio operators reported a tree down on Negus Way, a tree down on Clapp Road between Deerfield Terrace and Marys Pond Road, and a tree down on Burgess Avenue.

The storm system also brought 1 to 4 inches of snow to the east slopes of the Berkshires in northwest Massachusetts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Winds generally were gusting to around 55 mph.  The ASOS at Plymouth recorded a gust to 55 mph and a spotter in Falmouth recorded a gust to 57 mph.  In Lakeville at 502 AM EDT (402 AM EST), high tension power lines were down on Pickens Street near Precinct Street.  In Middleborough between 556 AM EDT (456 AM EST) and 621 AM EDT (521 AM EST), law enforcement reported a tree and wires down on Fuller Street and a tree down on Marion Road between Stony Point Road and Long Point Road.  In Hanson, a tree was down on Camp Kiwanee Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: One large high precipitation supercell formed near the Nebraska Kansas border and tracked south during the evening of June 11th producing widespread damaging straight line winds of 80-110 mph along with several small tornadoes.   The majority of property damage was done by straight line winds within what was the rear flank downdraft of the supercell which was moving south southwest.  The widespread destructive winds within the RFD often preceded any smaller vortex with the small tornadoes making damage from tornadoes difficult to distinguish from the downbursts and microbursts within the larger RFD swath.   We believe there were at least 5 tornadoes that evening all EF0 or EF1.  Ironically, the magnitude of damage from straight line winds in spots exceeded that of the smaller tornadoes.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm survey and storm chaser video and photos revealed a brief tornado just northeast of Marysville.  This tornado did damage to a barn and power pole short path.  The damage to a lumber shop south of highway 36 appears to have been related to a possible RFD surge south (straight line winds) and not this tornado.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cluster of storms moved out of Nebraska during the evening of June 7th and evolved into a line of storms that accelerated southeast across central and northeast Kansas. At least 2 small tornadoes occurred along with widespread damaging straight line winds of 60 to 80 mph.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm survey revealed a 50-75 yard path of concentrated damage done to several structures and a line of cedars that were topped off on the west side of the Big Blue River south of Marysville.  The damage path extended to the east side of the river where tree damage was noted in a focused area.

The widespread destructive winds within the RFD often preceded any smaller vortex with the small tornadoes making damage from tornadoes difficult to distinguish from the downbursts and microbursts within the larger RFD swath.   We believe there were at least 5 tornadoes that evening all EF0 or EF1.  Ironically, the magnitude of damage from straight line winds in spots exceeded that of the smaller tornadoes.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Damage survey revealed a garage was destroyed on the south side of state line road with debris thrown north back into Nebraska (across the road).  A sporadic damage path moved southeast and ended around highway 77 where power poles were broken along with some tree limb damage.   This tornado moved south out of Nebraska and ended in Kansas.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Another tornado path that was nearly indistinguishable from the widespread straight line wind damage that preceded it into the north side of Blue Rapids.  It appears that a tornado did damage along a path that traveled just north of a Georgia Pacific Plant along and just west of highway 77 where it derailed train cars then pushed south into the river bottoms snapping trees.  The track became very broad as it approached the river where it appears it transitioned to a damaging downburst surge of 100-105 mph straight line winds across the city of Blue Rapids with the worst damage on the west side of the city.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An atmospheric river impacted the Bay Area on December 31st, resulting in significant rainfall across the San Francisco Bay Area. Initial forecasts called for the most intense rainband to progressively move south towards the Central Coast as the day went on. However, the morning of the 31st, a surface low developed west of San Francisco, and the river stalled over the Bay Area. This resulted in significant rainfall totals for many Bay Area sites. Most notably, downtown San Francisco received 5.46 inches of rain on the 31st, the second wettest day on record. The Oakland Museum received its wettest day since records began in 1970, with 4.75 inches of rain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trained spotter reported 4.45 inches of rain from 5 PM on December 30 to 5 PM on December 31.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level short wave trough moving through northern New England combined with an advancing cold front to produce severe thunderstorms in the late afternoon and evening hours.  Despite low K Indices and dry air aloft, the storms managed to strengthen and the dry air helped enhance the severe wind gusts.  The storms mainly impacted areas from western MA east-southeastward into northern CT and northern RI.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: In Enfield at 614 PM EDT, police reported a tree was down on Mathewson Avenue...relayed by amateur radio.  Also in Enfield, at 616 PM EDT, amateur radio operators reported a large tree was down on Bailey Road.

Another cluster of heavy thunderstorms developed late in the evening in Mercer County and across the river in Bucks County, PA and tracked northeast producing locally heavy rainfall as well.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions improved significantly across western Kentucky during the month. The drought was no longer categorized as severe by the end of the month. Most crops had been harvested, so agricultural impacts were limited. Wildfire danger decreased greatly by late in the month. River levels increased, though some rivers remained below normal through the end of the month.

The evening of Sunday, February 20th, a large Arctic ridge of high pressure built southward across the Upper Midwest. Brisk north/northeasterly surface winds were across the Upper Midwest with an increasing area of (850-700 MB) low-level forcing preceding an upper trough over the northern Rockies. These two elements aided in the development of a narrow band of moderate to heavy snowfall that was first centered along the North Dakota, South Dakota border Sunday evening. Regional radar that evening showed an enhanced area of higher reflectivity that slowly spread eastward across central Minnesota late Sunday night, and into Monday morning before lifting northeast over the arrowhead of Minnesota. ||Snowfall rates of 1  to 2 inches per hour were noted over central Minnesota early Monday morning as modest forcing within the dendritic growth layer supported these type of rates.  By Monday afternoon, most of the snowfall tapered off to flurries or light snow will little additional accumulation until Monday night. ||A secondary wave developed across the central plains late Monday night. It was much |stronger than the previous wave and had more moisture surging northward into the system. Another area of light snow that affected central Minnesota Tuesday morning was broader but less intense. Although additional snow fell during this time period, the heaviest occurred during the first wave late Sunday night, and into Monday morning. ||Total snowfall amounts by Tuesday evening, led to a broad area of 6 to 14 inches of snow that fell from Morris, east-northeast to Sauk Centre, Rice, Princeton, and Rush City northward. Some of the highest totals occurred over Todd County where locally 14.3 inches fell near Bertha.  ||Some of the higher totals include:||Bertha in Todd County 14.3 inches.|South of Mora in Kanabec County 14.0 inches. |Clarissa in Todd County 14.0 inches.|Little Falls in Morrison County 13.0 inches.|North of Flensburg in Morrison County 13.0 inches.|Morris in Stevens County 12.4 inches. |Donnelly in Stevens County 10.5 inches.|West of Mora in Kanabec County 12.1 inches. |East of Motley in Morrison County 11.9 inches. |Long Prairie in Todd County 10.4 inches. |Isle in Mille Lacs County 9.1 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Light snow began across Todd County during the early morning of Monday, February 21st. Heavy snow fell during the morning, with up to 7 inches prior to 8 AM, Monday morning. There was a lull in the precipitation Monday afternoon and evening before a second wave of light to moderate snow fell across the county. Total snowfall amounts by time it ended ranged from 8 to 14 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Nicole formed as a subtropical storm about 600 miles east of the Bahamas on November 7th, then moved northwest. Nicole gained tropical characteristics and became a tropical storm on November 8th as it turned west and west-southwest. Nicole strengthened into a Category 1 hurricane on November 9th as it moved over Great Abaco and Grand Bahama islands. Nicole then turned to the northwest as it approached Florida, making landfall just south of Vero Beach at 3 AM on November 10th as a Category 1 hurricane with lowest central pressure of 981 mb. Nicole then was downgraded to a tropical storm while moving inland across Central Florida.||Nicole's large wind field west of the storm center led to tropical storm force winds over the local Atlantic waters and the SE Florida coast beginning on the afternoon of November 8th and continuing until the pre-dawn hours of November 10th. Tropical storm force winds also spread across Lake Okeechobee during the late night of November 9th and early morning of November 10th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind measurements from coastal locations, as well as data from hurricane hunter aircraft, indicated sustained winds in the 35-45 knot range/40-55 mph over the waters of Broward and Miami-Dade counties from 20 to 60 nm offshore.

A cluster of supercell thunderstorms moved through the region beginning on the evening of June 14 and continuing into the early morning hours of June 15. The storms produced widespread wind gusts of 75 to 115 mph, hail 1 to 3 inches in diameter, and two EF1 tornadoes. Minor flooding was also reported in Omaha. The storms caused widespread tree damage, and some structural damage to homes and businesses.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Emergency management reported a measured peak wind gust of 61 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cluster of supercell thunderstorms moved through the region beginning on the evening of June 14 and continuing into the early morning hours of June 15. The storms produced widespread wind gusts of 75 to 115 mph, hail 1 to 3 inches in diameter, and two EF1 tornadoes. Minor flooding was also reported in Omaha. The storms caused widespread tree damage, and some structural damage to homes and businesses.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tornado developed near Church Road west of 298th Street and immediately damaged a home. One of the roof peaks was torn off and garage doors blown in. The damage here was very focused as nearby trees were not damaged, but insulation from the home was stuck to 3 different sides of the home, indicating this was likely a tornado. Farther east, there was an area of focused tree damage approximately 150 yards wide embedded within a several mile wide area of more minor tree damage. The tornado continued east where it snapped several power poles and caused minor damage to a church. Additional damage to grain bins and trees was noted along Church road just west of 322nd street, which appears to be the end of the focused damage most likely caused by the tornado. This tornado occurred within a several mile wide area of intense straight-line wind damage which was caused by winds at times greater than 80 mph.

A moisture-rich environment was in place on the 24th with PWAT values climbing upwards of 2 across south-central Arizona. A weak disturbance embedded in the flow aided in shower and thunderstorm development to persist out of southeast Arizona and into central portions of the state. Given the amount of moisture in the environment, thunderstorms were able to produce locally heavy rainfall which led to isolated flash flooding in southern Maricopa County. By the afternoon, daytime heating aided in new thunderstorm development across southeast Arizona, which eventually produced a strong outflow traveling northward into Pinal County. The strong outflow boundary generated isolated dense blowing dust in Pinal County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: State Route 238 was closed between Gila Bend and Maricopa due to flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Warm, moist, and unstable air spread north across North and East Texas, North Louisiana, and extreme Southern Arkansas during the evening through the early morning hours of April 4th-5th, behind a warm front that lifted north through these areas. Meanwhile, an upper trough dug through Western Texas and into the Southern Plains during the afternoon and evening hours of the 4th, enhancing large scale forcing along and ahead of a dry line that developed and spread east across North-central Texas. This resulted in shower and thunderstorm development which rapidly intensified over this area, which spread east into East Texas and Southeast Oklahoma during the late evening hours of the 4th. Given the extent of elevated instability and the strong southerly low level jet in place across Southeast Oklahoma, these storms became severe as they spread east across McCurtain County, resulting in multiple reports of hail as these storms organized into a quasi-linear convective system (QLCS) which quickly spread across the region through the pre-dawn hours. These storms exited Southeast Oklahoma by midnight that night.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail fell in the Garvin community.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front crossed Pennsylvania during the early morning hours of March 12, 2022. A few rain showers accompanied the front across the area, and then a wave of low pressure developed along the front as it slowly pulled east of central Pennsylvania. As steadier precipitation arrived, colder air arrived behind the front and changed the rain over to snow from northwest to southeast across the area into the mid-morning of March 12. A relatively short-lived period of moderate to heavy snow produced widespread 4 to 6 inches of snow, with localized amounts approaching 10 inches. Gusty northwest winds resulted in considerable blowing snow and reduced visibilities for many locations by the afternoon of March 12, as low pressure continued northeastward and rapidly intensified off the New England coast.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A winter storm produced 4 to 6 inches of snow across Lebanon County in less than 12 hours on March 12, 2022.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Warm, moist, and unstable air spread north across North and East Texas, North Louisiana, and extreme Southern Arkansas during the evening through the early morning hours of April 4th-5th, behind a warm front that lifted north through these areas. Meanwhile, an upper trough dug through Western Texas and into the Southern Plains during the afternoon and evening hours of the 4th, enhancing large scale forcing along and ahead of a dry line that developed and spread east across North-central Texas. This resulted in shower and thunderstorm development which rapidly intensified over this area, which spread east into East Texas and Southeast Oklahoma during the late evening hours of the 4th. Given the extent of elevated instability and the strong southerly low level jet in place across Southeast Oklahoma, these storms became severe as they spread east across McCurtain County, resulting in multiple reports of hail as these storms organized into a quasi-linear convective system (QLCS) which quickly spread across the region through the pre-dawn hours. These storms exited Southeast Oklahoma by midnight that night.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail fell in Idabel.

CZ_NAME: LONG ISLAND SOUND EAST OF NEW HAVEN CT/PORT JEFFERSON NY TO THE MOUTH OF THE CONNECTICUT RIVER
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A broad upper level trough and associated surface trough moved through the area during the afternoon/evening hours. With cyclonic flow aloft, daytime heating resulted in the development of showers that produced gusty winds and small hail. Winds over 34 knots were recorded over the waters.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Mesonet station XLTH at Lighthouse Point CT measured a 36 knot wind gust.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front crossed Pennsylvania during the early morning hours of March 12, 2022. A few rain showers accompanied the front across the area, and then a wave of low pressure developed along the front as it slowly pulled east of central Pennsylvania. As steadier precipitation arrived, colder air arrived behind the front and changed the rain over to snow from northwest to southeast across the area into the mid-morning of March 12. A relatively short-lived period of moderate to heavy snow produced widespread 4 to 6 inches of snow, with localized amounts approaching 10 inches. Gusty northwest winds resulted in considerable blowing snow and reduced visibilities for many locations by the afternoon of March 12, as low pressure continued northeastward and rapidly intensified off the New England coast.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A winter storm produced 5 to 6 inches of snow across Adams County in less than 12 hours on March 12, 2022.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak synoptic-scale wave progressed through the area atop a flat upper-level ridge, initiating several clusters of thunderstorms during the afternoon and early evening.  Storms developed near a weak convergence zone, in an environment of 1000-2000 J/kg MLCAPE and marginally strong deep-layer shear of 30 knots.  Mainly multi-cell clusters resulted in marginally severe damaging wind gusts due to sub-cloud dryness and marginally large hail.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An expansive ridge of high pressure aloft forced a strong warm plume to the northeast, ahead of a frontal boundary on August 5.  The combination of temperatures in the mid to upper 90s and dew point readings in the mid 60s to around 70 led to heat index values from 105-110 for several hours across south central and southeast South Dakota.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Temperatures in the upper 90s and dew point readings in the upper 60s resulted in heat index values as high as 109 degrees at Armour.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered thunderstorms developed across south-central South Dakota in the late afternoon of August 2nd in response to an eastward advancing short-wave aloft. Weak deep-layer shear and skinny CAPE profiles limited the overall severe threat, but a very dry sub-cloud layer allowed for stronger wind gusts aloft to reach the surface across portions of southeast South Dakota and southwest Minnesota during the evening hours. Observed wind gusts ranged from 60 to 80 mph with occasional reports of trees down and isolated structural damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A thunderstorm wind gust of 74 mph was measured by Automated Weather Observing System site KMML 1 mile west of Marshall.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed toward midnight on leading elevated warm advection across south central South Dakota and progressed rapidly northeast through areas north of Interstate 90.  Large amounts of DCAPE in the air mass resulted in spotty damaging wind.  A second cluster of storms developed on the tail end of the initial storms on the nose of an increasing low-level jet, using up to 2000 J/kg of elevated instability to rapidly become severe.  Very large hail resulted as storms first developed supercellular characteristics, and then a mix of hail and damaging wind as short bowing segments evolved moving into northwest Iowa and southwest Minnesota.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front, that was draped northeast-southwest across western Iowa and eastern Nebraska/Kansas, moved south and entered the county warning area during the morning of February 1st.  Broad moist isentropic ascent and overrunning precipitation developed across the entire county warning area gradually through the late morning into the afternoon of February 1st, with the baroclinic zone initially serving as the focus for rain. This first round of precipitation stayed nearly all rain, but snow did begin to mix with rain in northern Missouri and west-central Illinois during the afternoon hours of February 1st as colder air advanced south behind the front.  The cold air became more established in the northwest half of the CWA with wet snow and a snowfall rate approaching 1/hr across parts of northeast Missouri and west central Illinois north of the I-70 corridor during the early morning hours of February 2nd.  The first round brought a wide swath of at least 6-10 inches of snow (with some sleet mixed in) across central/east-central Missouri and west-central Illinois. A second round of heavy snow fell along and south of the I-70 corridor with snowfall rates in excess of 0.5 per hour and occasionally brief periods of 1.5 per hour on Thursday, February 3rd.  An additional 6-8 of snow fell in this area during the morning/afternoon hours of February 3rd with lighter snowfall over northeast Missouri and west central Illinois.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: As temperatures dropped during the late evening hours, rain changed over to freezing rain. By midnight on February 2nd, around one to two tenths of an inch of icing was reported across Montgomery County. Then the liquid precipitation changed over to snow. Between eight to ten inches of snow fell across Montgomery County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A coastal storm moved northward from the mid-Atlantic coast late on the 18th to interior New England during the pre-dawn morning hours on the 19th.  Locally heavy rainfall helped bring down damaging wind gusts from a low-level jet across Rhode Island and southeast Massachusetts.  The storm system also brought 1 to 4 inches of snow to the east slopes of the Berkshires in northwest Massachusetts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Winds generally were gusting to around 50 mph.  In Boston at 454 AM EDT (354 AM EST), the ASOS at Logan International Airport (KBOS) recorded a gust to 46 mph.  In Boston at 359 AM EDT (259 AM EST), police reported a tree down on a car on Camden Street (relayed by amateur radio).

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak cold front triggered isolated severe thunderstorms in eastern Connecticut during the early evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: In Columbia, a billboard was blown down on Route 66 East.  Trees were downed on Cherry Valley Road, Flanders River Road, Cards Mill Road, and Old Willimantic Road.  A tree and wires were down on both Newberry Road and on Devonshire Lane, per the Fire Department.  Reports were relayed to NWS via amateur radio operators.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered showers and thunderstorms developed across the region as a frontal system pushed through. A few of these storms became severe downing trees and power lines. A localized area of widespread straight-line wind damage occurred near Earlton in Greene County downing trees and wires as well as damaging structures.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A severe thunderstorm produced localized straight-line wind damage about 1 mile east of Earlton along New York Route 81. Wind descended down a hill south of Route 81 and moved north-northeastward across the road. Damage consisted of numerous snapped or uprooted trees and large branches, a broken metal windmill and the destruction of one tractor shed. Additionally, there was wind damage to the flashing of one house and two other homes were damaged by falling trees. Another house was damaged when a falling tree ripped electrical wires from it which pulled off some siding. Winds were estimated at 85 mph with a path length of one-quarter of a mile and path width of 200 yards.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level short wave trough moving through northern New England combined with an advancing cold front to produce severe thunderstorms in the late afternoon and evening hours.  Despite low K Indices and dry air aloft, the storms managed to strengthen and the dry air helped enhance the severe wind gusts.  The storms mainly impacted areas from western MA east-southeastward into northern CT and northern RI.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: In Glocester, a tree was down on Hunting House Road and a tree was down on Cranberry Ridge Road.  A little farther east, two large limbs were down on Snake Hill Road at Paris Irons Road.  Reports relayed via amateur radio operators.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered showers and thunderstorms developed during the afternoon hours on August 17, 2022 in association with a disturbance off the Northeast US coast. These storms tracked from northeast to southwest. Damage was mainly confined to the Capital Region where a severe thunderstorm downed some trees and power lines across the region. In addition, sub-severe wind gusts led to some flying debris at the New York State Food Festival which was being held in Albany. Event managers cancelled the remainder of the event following the storm.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Large swells from the the northwest and north generated surf of 10 to 20 feet, with occasionally higher sets to 25 feet, along the north- and west-facing shores of Niihau and Kauai, and along the north-facing shores of Oahu and Molokai; 8 to 15 feet, with occasionally higher sets to 20 feet, along the west facing shores of Oahu and Molokai, and north facing shores of Maui and the Big Island.  The surf kept lifeguards and other ocean safety officials busy with rescues and issuing warnings.  No serious injuries or property damage were reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A winter storm brought heavy snow to the Cascades shortly after the start of the New Year.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow began in the Central Cascades during the early afternoon hours of January 2. About 12 inches of snow fell within a 12 hour period. Snow then continued at Stevens Pass through the 3rd before tapering during the very late evening hours on the 4th.  Total storm snowfall at Stevens Pass for this event was around 20 inches. ||For Snoqualmie Pass, snow also began during the early afternoon hours on the 2nd, quickly accumulating to over a foot and a half by early the next morning. As snow tapered late on the 4th, total snowfall for the event was around 2 feet.
