EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Abnormally dry and warm conditions continued across western and north central Nebraska in October. Drought conditions deteriorated across all of western and north central Nebraska. With the exception of moderate (D1) drought conditions in most of Sheridan County, all of western and north central Nebraska had drought conditions ranging from severe (D2) to exceptional (D4) drought by the end of October.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Across far southern Rock county, severe (D2) drought conditions deteriorated to extreme (D3) drought conditions by the end of October. Across the remainder of the county, extreme (D3) drought conditions persisted through the end of the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Abundant moisture was drawn north across the region from the 14th into the 15th in advance of a slow moving cold front. Areas of heavy rain lifted north in advance of the front...enhanced by several lows lifting north along the slow moving front. The heaviest rains occurred from the overnight hours of the 14th into the morning of the 15th. Flash flooding developed in both the Bangor/Brewer and Lincoln/Mattawamkeag areas during the early morning hours of the 15th. Numerous roads were closed and impassable due to flash flooding...with vehicles also disabled. Water rescues were also required around Bangor/Brewer with up to 4 feet of standing water reported at some locations. Several roads were also closed in the Lincoln/Mattawamkeag area including Route 155 and Old Military Road. Old Military Road was partially collapsed due to rushing water overwhelming a culvert. Other roads and culverts were also damaged to varying extents across southern and central Penobscot county. Rainfall totals generally ranged from 2.50 to 4.50 inches...with local totals in excess of 5.00 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flash flooding developed during the early morning hours of the 15th around the Bangor/Brewer area. Numerous roads were closed and impassable due to the flash flooding. Some water rescues were also required...with standing water up to 4 feet deep in some locations. Several vehicles were also disabled due to the flash flood waters. Some roads and culverts in the area were damaged to varying extents. Rainfall totals with this event generally ranged from 2.50 to 4.50 inches...with local totals in excess of 5.00 inches.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Exceptional (D4) drought conditions persisted through the end of October over all of Hayes county. The cooperative observer at Hayes Center reported 0.33 inches of precipitation in October. This was 1.34 inches below the normal of 1.67 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A tropical depression brought a brief period of strong winds and heavy rain to Palau.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: On the 27th of October a circulation was located near 7N145E and was classified as Invest 94W. By the 30th 94W had moved to 9N138E. On the morning of the 31st 94W intensified to Tropical Depression 27W at 8N135E or 60 miles north-northeast of Koror, Palau. ||On the 31st, IR satellite imagery showed that TD 27W to be highly sheared under|northeast winds of 35 to 50 kt at 200 mb. As a result, the low-level center was partially exposed on the northeast side of the deep convection, which is seen mainly in the southwest quadrant of the circulation over Palau. The deep convection itself is very|intense, with frequent lightning and cloud tops as cold as -91C.||These showers and thunderstorms passed over Palau with thousands of lightning|bolts detected between 21Z and 00Z or 6 am to 9 am local time. These lightning|bolts fell across the main island of Babeldaob. ||Winds gust to 48 knots (55 mph) was observed at the Palau Weather Office on Babeldaob at 2150Z. Between 8 and 9 am winds gusts to 42 mph was recorded with an automated weather sensor of the Rock Islands. ||Power was knocked out by TD27W and some trees were reported to be down ||By the afternoon of the 31st 27W was upgraded to a tropical storm, eventually |being named Banyan. At this time the tropical storm was about 65 miles west-northwest of Koror and moving away at 15 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Persistent dry weather caused drought conditions to begin in Kapingamarangi.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rainfall decreased at Kapingamarangi which caused it to go from Moderate Drought (D1) to Severe Drought (D2). Kapingamarangi public and private water tanks are around 50% capacity. Crops are stressed from the recent dry weather.

Abnormally dry and warm conditions continued across western and north central Nebraska in October. Drought conditions deteriorated across all of western and north central Nebraska. EVENT_NARRATIVE: Severe (D2) drought conditions persisted over the northern half of Garden county in October. Extreme (D3) drought conditions expanded from the far southeastern portion of Garden county into the southern half of the county by the end of the month. The cooperative observer at Crescent Lakes NWR reported 0.63 inches of precipitation in October. This was 0.63 inches below the normal of 1.26 inches. The cooperative observer at Oshkosh reported 0.38 inches of precipitation in October. This was 0.95 inches below the normal of 1.33 inches. The cooperative observer at Oshkosh 10NE reported 0.37 inches of precipitation in October.

This was 1.62 inches below the normal of 1.62 inches. The cooperative observer at Ellsworth 2W reported 0.54 inches of precipitation for October. This was 0.60 inches below the normal of 1.14 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A potent upper-level storm system moving slowly southeast toward NM on October 23, 2022 combined with a deep area of surface low pressure along the Front Range to produce widespread strong winds across the region. Wind gusts of 50 to 60 mph first developed along the central high terrain during the early morning hours before spreading into the nearby highlands and northeast plains of NM through the afternoon. The highest wind gusts impacted the area around Ruidoso where gusts near 70 mph were reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Gallup airport reported a peak wind gust to 61 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Another month of above normal precipitation brought almost all of southern New Mexico out of Severe(D2) drought or worse.  By the end of October, only a a small area around the New Mexico Bootheel remained in Severe drought.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Severe(D2) drought remained over the far northwest part of the zone to start the month and improved to no drought over the southeast.  By the end of October, all areas were in Abnormally Dry(D0) drought except the southeast where no drought existed. The Cooperative Observer at New Mexico State University reported 1.56 inches of precipitation which was 0.74 inches above normal.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cutoff upper low was sitting over the northern Gulf of California with a 90 knot jet moving over southern New Mexico.  These features combined with a cold front dropping out of the north to bring heavy rain and severe storms to the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A video was taken at the intersection of Superstition Drive and Remington Road showing flash flooding occurring. Small hail was also falling in the area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front pushed through central Georgia on the evening of October 12th, producing showers and embedded strong to isolated severe thunderstorms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A brief tornado crossed Hwy 149 about a mile southeast of Racetrack Road, southeast of the town of McRae in Telfair County. The tornado was on the ground for less than a 1/2 mile and snapped or uprooted trees along its path.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A complex winter storm brought a mixture of rain, sleet and freezing rain to most of the region, with snow in the mountains, on Sunday January 16th. The mixed precipitation changed to snow from west to east during the late afternoon into the evening and the snow fell heavily at times overnight and early Monday morning. As the parent storm system moved to our northeast, the snow became more showery in nature into Monday afternoon, with snow showers lingering in the mountains through Tuesday morning.||While the heaviest snow occurred in the West Virginia mountains, with 12 to 18 inches reported, another swath of heavy snow occurred up the Ohio River Valley region of West Virginia, where 6 to 10 inches occurred. For the rest of the state, generally 4 to 8 inches fell. The snow began wet and heavy, which caused power outages where the heaviest snow fell. Over 25,000 West Virginians were without power Monday morning.
A moist tropical airmass pushed over Lee County bringing heavy rain and street flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Skywarn spotter reported flooded roadway at intersection of College Parkway and Winkler  Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large, deep, and cold upper level low remained situated over eastern Idaho and western Wyoming. Ample moisture associated with this system paired with modest instability from clearing skies resulted in the development of some stronger thunderstorms across western Colorado. Ping pong ball sized hail fell with a storm in Montrose County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ping pong ball sized hail fell in Nucla in Montrose County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Significant clearing late in the morning resulted in the development of high instability across western Colorado. This, paired with upper level support and ample moisture, produced strong to severe thunderstorms across the area in the late afternoon and early evening hours. Severe wind gusts up to 61 mph occurred in Garfield County. Additionally, heavy rain occurred with storms which led to flash flooding and debris flows across portions of San Miguel, Montrose, and Mesa counties.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A peak wind gust of 61 MPH was measured by the automated weather station at the Rifle Garfield County Airport.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Skies cleared in the wake of a departing upper level low. This led to subfreezing temperatures in the Upper Yampa River Basin where vegetation was susceptible to damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Overnight lows ranged from 29 to 32 degrees across the area, including a low of 32 degrees at the Bob Adams Field Airport.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Overnight lows ranged from 22 to 32 degrees across the area. This was a season-ending freeze for the Lower Yampa River Basin.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An anomalously strong and unseasonably cold Pacific trough progressed inland across the western United States. Strong southwest winds occurred out ahead of the trough and along the cold front across all of western Colorado. Winds gusted in the 40 to 50 mph range for the valleys with gusts of 60 mph or more in the mountains. This led to widespread blowing snow in the higher elevations which, when paired with moderate to heavy snow, resulted in near blizzard conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 3 to 6 inches of snow fell across the area with locally higher amounts of up to 12 inches estimated at the Schofield Pass SNOTEL site.

A potent upper level low pressure system over New Mexico shifted east across Western and North Texas south of the Red River during the afternoon and evening hours of October 24th, which allowed for a dry line to mix east across Texas. A cold front extended east of this upper low over Eastern Oklahoma and Northeast Texas, with the dry line eventually overtaking the front but provided strong forcing for a linear line of showers and thunderstorms to develop during the evening and overnight hours as they entered East Texas. Although instability was limited given cooler conditions during the latter evening hours, strong shear resulted in a well-organized line of strong to severe thunderstorms along these surface features, producing damaging winds which downed trees across portions of East Texas before the storms weakened further upon entering Western Louisiana during the early morning hours on the 25th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple trees were blown down on Highway 315 several miles northeast of Mount Enterprise.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A potent upper level low pressure system over New Mexico shifted east across Western and North Texas south of the Red River during the afternoon and evening hours of October 24th, which allowed for a dry line to mix east across Texas. A cold front extended east of this upper low over Eastern Oklahoma and Northeast Texas, with the dry line eventually overtaking the front but provided strong forcing for a linear line of showers and thunderstorms to develop during the evening and overnight hours as they entered East Texas. Although instability was limited given cooler conditions during the latter evening hours, strong shear resulted in a well-organized line of strong to severe thunderstorms along these surface features, producing damaging winds which downed trees across portions of East Texas before the storms weakened further upon entering Western Louisiana during the early morning hours on the 25th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were blown down on Highway 69.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Severe (D2) drought conditions continued across parts of Southwest Arkansas during October. This was in response to an extended flash drought that resulted from an exceptionally hot and dry month in June with below normal rainfall in what is historically one of the wettest months on average. This was followed up by an even hotter and drier month in July with the total rainfall amounts for July generally around an inch or less, which was only near 25% of normal. Near normal rainfall occurred in August, but hot and dry conditions returned in September with below normal rainfall while October rainfall was near normal. This dryness contributed to lower than normal streamflow observed across area creeks, streams, and rivers.

A potent upper-level storm system moving slowly southeast toward NM on October 23, 2022 combined with a deep area of surface low pressure along the Front Range to produce widespread strong winds across the region. Wind gusts of 50 to 60 mph first developed along the central high terrain during the early morning hours before spreading into the nearby highlands and northeast plains of NM through the afternoon. The highest wind gusts impacted the area around Ruidoso where gusts near 70 mph were reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Sierra Blanca Regional Airport reported an extended period of high sustained winds between 40 mph and 50 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Another month of above normal precipitation brought almost all of southern New Mexico out of Severe(D2) drought or worse.  By the end of October, only a a small area around the New Mexico Bootheel remained in Severe drought.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The month started with Severe(D2) drought across the central part of the zone extending from southwest to northeast with Moderate(D1) drought elsewhere. By the end of the month the whole zone was in Abnormally Dry(D0) drought. The Deming Airport reported 2.35 inches of precipitation which was 1.60 inches above normal.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cutoff upper low was sitting over the northern Gulf of California with a 90 knot jet moving over southern New Mexico.  These features combined with a cold front dropping out of the north to bring heavy rain and severe storms to the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A military meteorologist reported quarter sized hail at Interstate 25 mile marker 21.  The interstate was covered with hail from marker 20 to 25.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cutoff upper low was sitting over the northern Gulf of California with a 90 knot jet moving over southern New Mexico.  These features combined with a cold front dropping out of the north to bring heavy rain and severe storms to the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail the size of quarters fell for several minutes.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep upper trough moved through the Western United States with strong southwest flow including a 120 knot jet ahead of it across southern New Mexico.  Several reports just short of 60 mph were received with some damage near the White Sands Headquarters.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown onto a power line and roofing materials were flying off and damaging cars.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A quick moving but strong storm system brought a variety of weather to the region on the 17th, with strong to isolated severe storms across central and southern Oklahoma and heavy snow falling across northern Oklahoma. Strong winds also occurred on the backside of the storm, with occasional gusts over 60 mph reported. High winds led to near blizzard conditions at times during the morning of the 17th.

Abnormally dry and warm conditions continued across western and north central Nebraska in October. Drought conditions deteriorated across all of western and north central Nebraska. With the exception of moderate (D1) drought conditions in most of Sheridan County, all of western and north central Nebraska had drought conditions ranging from severe (D2) to exceptional (D4) drought by the end of October.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate (D1) drought conditions over far southeastern Garfield county, deteriorated to severe (D2) drought conditions by the end of October. Across the remainder of Garfield county, severe (D2) drought conditions deteriorated to extreme (D3) drought conditions by the end of the month. The cooperative observer at Ericson 8WNW reported 0.80 inches of precipitation in October. This was 1.35 inches below the normal of 2.15 inches. The cooperative observer at Burwell reported 0.33 inches of precipitation in October. This was 1.80 inches below the normal of 2.13 inches.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Extreme (D3) drought conditions persisted over far southern Keya Paha county through the end of October. Across the remainder of the county, severe (D2) drought conditions deteriorated to extreme (D3) drought conditions by the end of October. The cooperative observer at Springview 2NW reported 0.50 inches of precipitation in October. This was 1.01 inches below the normal of 1.51 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A southeaster storm brought widespread gusty winds to Maine that downed branches and a few trees causing power outages to the region.  Winds remained below high wind warning criteria but gusts mostly in the 40 to 50 mph range along with heavy rain still downed numerous branches and trees causing scattered power outages across Coastal and Western Maine.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Gusty southeast winds through the day on October 14th along with heavy rain caused numerous snapped branches and a few downed standing dead trees.  Power outages in Southwest Maine peaked at 69,500 outages during the afternoon hours when the peak wind gusts were occurring.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Several widespread, heavy rain events during October helped ease the drought across much of far eastern Oklahoma during the month. However, the remainder of eastern Oklahoma, especially areas north of I-40 and west of Highway 69, received below average precipitation for the month, much of that area only receiving between 25 and 50 percent of average rainfall amounts. As a result, exceptional drought (D4) conditions expanded across portions of northeastern Oklahoma to include all of Washington, Nowata, and Rogers Counties, as well as portions of Cherokee, Wagoner, Tulsa, Mayes, Ottawa, Craig, and Osage Counties. Exceptional drought (D4) conditions also continued across portions of Pittsburg, McIntosh, Okmulgee, and Okfuskee Counties. Severe (D2) to extreme (D3) drought conditions persisted across the remainder of eastern Oklahoma through the month, although as noted previously, some improvement did occur across far eastern Oklahoma. Monetary damage estimates as a result of the drought were not available.

A strong area of low pressure across the Northern Plains lifted a warm front across the Northland on Memorial Day morning. Showers and storms moved through during the morning hours with the atmosphere recovering during the afternoon hours. A few of the storms were severe during the morning and produced small hail and tree damage. An arc of thunderstorms developed across southwestern Minnesota and adjacent areas of Nebraska, South Dakota and Iowa by the mid-afternoon hours and moved to the northeast and across the Northland for the late afternoon and evening hours. These storms were much stronger and contained very strong winds that produced widespread damage across the region. Additionally, there were a few embedded tornadoes with the storms with the strongest tornadoes producing EF-1 damage in the Deer River and Hinckley areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Three power poles were snapped near Cook along with several trees down on power lines.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very localized tornado outbreak Saturday afternoon and evening as an unstable airmass developed over Mobile and Baldwin counties along with the western Florida panhandle ahead of an approaching cold front. Twelve tornadoes were found with 5 in Mobile County, 6 in Baldwin County and 1 tornado in Okaloosa County, FL.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A waterspout moved onshore the afternoon of the 30th, tossing and|destroying a large shed based on numerous eyewitness reports and|video. The tornado was rated EF0 with winds up to 85mph. The|tornado dissipated quickly before reaching Highway 98.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very localized tornado outbreak Saturday afternoon and evening as an unstable airmass developed over Mobile and Baldwin counties along with the western Florida panhandle ahead of an approaching cold front. Twelve tornadoes were found with 5 in Mobile County, 6 in Baldwin County and 1 tornado in Okaloosa County, FL. Two waterspouts were also reported in Mobile Bay.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Social media report of a waterspout just south of the mouth of Dog River off Bay Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions across northwestern Wisconsin during the month of October were fairly steady state with just a slight expansion of D2 Severe Drought near Chequamegon Bay during the middle of the month. Overall, precipitation was only about 25-50% of normal for the month, but no significant expansion of D2 Severe Drought was observed across the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Dry conditions persisted across Ashland County during the month of October. Just under an inch of precipitation was recorded for the month at the Ashland airport which was nearly two inches below normal. Despite this only minor expansion of D2 Severe Drought was seen with the update on the 11th. The area of D2 Severe Drought was confined to the far northwestern corner of the county near Chequamegon Bay. No further changes were noted over the remainder of the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The wet trend continued by the end of the month as another TUTT approaches the area. At first, this mid to upper level feature combined with moisture being pulling from the deep tropics into the region. Later in the period, a tropical wave was added to the mixture, further increasing moisture content and instability. A Flash Flood Watch was issued due to the excessive rainfall expected.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Emergency managers reported that road PR-181, near El Verde, was near impassable due to flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Several rounds of storms occurred on the 4th as a large trough approached the region. Initially several storms developed across northwest Oklahoma with large hail, with new storm development then occurring along and south of a warm front in central Oklahoma during the afternoon. These storms produced several tornadoes, along with hail and damaging wind gusts. Another round of storms moved in from the Texas panhandle during the evening of the 4th, bringing more tornadoes, hail, and wind. Localized flooding was also reported due to storms training over the same areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Time estimate from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Surface low pressure moved from the Middle Mississippi Valley into the Great Lakes while a trailing cold front swept across the Mid-South on November 29, 2022. Clusters of storms developed during the late morning as a warm front lifted north ahead of the main system. Some of these storms were severe with large hail over northeast Mississippi. During the evening a second round of showers and thunderstorms developed and eventually formed a line that exited the region into Alabama by midnight.  This second round resulted in scattered severe storms with large hail and damaging winds across the Memphis metropolitan area and again across northeast Mississippi.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A few trees down across the area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front moved through Eastern Colorado.  Ahead of the front southwest winds gusted up to 64 MPH, with the highest reported gust occurring at Burlington.  High winds from the southwest are rather unusual given that the vast majority of high wind events occur with northwest winds.  There was also blowing dust reported with the high winds, which caused visibilities to be reduced to less than two miles at times.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Reported near Firstview.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of storms moved through the region with a cold front. A couple cells became severe producing a tornado and wind damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The tornado started near the Calcasieu River near Mike Manuel Road. As it moved northeast, a tree was blown into a manufactured home and the front porch awning was ripped off. Another home had a damaged carport which fell onto a car. Several softwood trees were snapped off at the tops with a couple of hardwood trees snapped off near their bases. A third small industrial building on the property sustained damage to its roll-up shop door and a nearby parked and loaded construction trailer was pushed 4 to 6 feet to the east. The tornado lifted after this point, although its |circulation remained close to the surface as noted by bent and snapped softwood trees down Mike Manuel Road. The maximum estimated winds were 111 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Another round of Santa Ana winds impacted Southern California on November 19th and 20th.

The Marshall Peak mesonet site recorded a peak wind gust of 81 mph. The Arrowhead Springs SoCal-Edison mesonet site also recorded a peak wind gust of 69 mph.

Winds remained strong during much of the 24th with high wind gusts occurring throughout the morning, afternoon, and into the evening hours. The Fremont Canyon RAWS site recorded a peak wind gust of 59 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A surface trough moving from the southeast and south, and an upper low far west of the islands created instability statewide.  These features produced heavy showers and thunderstorms over portions of the state.  Rainfall was particularly intense over parts of Oahu, Kauai, and the Big Island which led to flash flooding.  There were no reports of serious injuries.  The costs of any damages were not available.  This episode is a continuation from the end of December.

Several widespread, heavy rain events during October helped ease the drought across much of far eastern Oklahoma during the month. However, the remainder of eastern Oklahoma, especially areas north of I-40 and west of Highway 69, received below average precipitation for the month, much of that area only receiving between 25 and 50 percent of average rainfall amounts. As a result, exceptional drought (D4) conditions expanded across portions of northeastern Oklahoma to include all of Washington, Nowata, and Rogers Counties, as well as portions of Cherokee, Wagoner, Tulsa, Mayes, Ottawa, Craig, and Osage Counties. Exceptional drought (D4) conditions also continued across portions of Pittsburg, McIntosh, Okmulgee, and Okfuskee Counties. Severe (D2) to extreme (D3) drought conditions persisted across the remainder of eastern Oklahoma through the month, although as noted previously, some improvement did occur across far eastern Oklahoma. Monetary damage estimates as a result of the drought were not available.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Widespread dense fog reduced visibility to one-quarter mile or less across far west Kentucky during the early morning hours. The dense fog was along and west of a line from Hopkinsville to Princeton to Marion. The dense fog formed in the vicinity of a surface trough of low pressure extending from north to south along the Mississippi River.

A strong area of low pressure across the Northern Plains lifted a warm front across the Northland on Memorial Day morning. Showers and storms moved through during the morning hours with the atmosphere recovering during the afternoon hours. A few of the storms were severe during the morning and produced small hail and tree damage. An arc of thunderstorms developed across southwestern Minnesota and adjacent areas of Nebraska, South Dakota and Iowa by the mid-afternoon hours and moved to the northeast and across the Northland for the late afternoon and evening hours. These storms were much stronger and contained very strong winds that produced widespread damage across the region. Additionally, there were a few embedded tornadoes with the storms with the strongest tornadoes producing EF-1 damage in the Deer River and Hinckley areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A photo was received of an estimated 10 to 12 inch diameter pine tree down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An arctic front draped across the VT-Canadian border during the morning of February 3rd and slowly drifted south across VT during the day and evening hours before temporarily stalling along the VT/MA border until the afternoon of February 4th. Light precipitation moved across VT during the morning of February 3rd morning, initially falling as light rain before changing primarily to light snow during the afternoon for much of VT except the southern four counties. ||During the late evening and overnight hours of February 3rd into the midday hours of February 4th, a series of weak low pressure areas moved northeast along the aforementioned boundary as this boundary slowly draped south along the VT/MA border. Moderate to heavy snow at times (>1 inch/hr) moved across much of VT during the night of February 3rd into midday of February 4th. Meanwhile in southern Rutland and southern Windsor counties, especially further south toward the MA border, freezing rain and sleet fell until the early morning hours of the 4th with some icing and ice/snow weighted trees causing some power outages.||Storm total snowfall ranged from 4 to 8 inches across the extreme southern portions of Windsor and Rutland counties where sleet and ice were prevalent as well to 12 to 16 inches elsewhere across central and northern VT.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Total snowfall ranged from 8 to 12 inches with much of this falling in the late evening of February 3rd to around daybreak on February 4th. In extreme southern portions, freezing rain and sleet were prevalent through the early morning hours with some ice accumulation as well.

A strong cold front plowed across New York and triggered a narrow line of enhanced showers with little lightning. The line increased in strength over eastern Lake Ontario and continued across Jefferson and Lewis counties. A few notches were noted on the line on radar in a marginally favorable environment for weak tornadic spin-ups. While velocity values on radar were unimpressive for a tornado, and no tornado was observed, some wind damage did occur in Lewis County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and wires were reported down in Lowville.

Unseasonably warm temperatures, strong wind gusts, and very low humidity combined with dormant, drought-stricken fuels to promote conditions that supported the rapid spread of wildfire across portions of northeastern Oklahoma during late October. Numerous wildfires occurred from the 21st through the 23rd across the region, but the largest fires affected Osage County where over 15,000 acres were burned, Pawnee County where over 6000 acres were burned, and Rogers County where over 5000 acres were burned. A fire fighter was injured in the Pawnee County fires on the 22nd.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Pre-frontal strong thunderstorms moved offshore of the NE FL Atlantic coast in the mid-afternoon.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A shortwave trough moved through the upper pattern and pushed a cold front through South Central Texas. Thunderstorms developed along this front and produced damaging wind gusts and one tornado.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A National Weather Service storm survey team determined a tornado touched down just west of CR 234 and north of CR 239. The tornado moved southeastward producing EF-0 damage to trees and a barn and knocked down a two-story home that was still under construction near CR 310 and CR 237. As the tornado crossed this intersection it turned east and strengthened and widened. High end EF-0 damage was observed to trees and some homes just to the west of I-35. The tornado crossed I-35 south of CR 314 and north of Ronald Reagan Blvd. and strengthened further. A semi-trailer was flipped on I-35 and the driver sustained minor injuries. Nine wooden power poles were brought down on the north bound side of I-35, including one that was snapped in half. As the tornado continued east of I-35 and west of Little Road EF-1 damage was observed. Additional power poles were damaged and snapped. A home sustained roof damage and many large tree branches were snapped. A barn had a portion of the roof removed. A small, enclosed cargo trailer on the property was lofted roughly 100 yards downwind. Maximum winds were estimated at 100 mph just east of I-35. The tornado dissipated east of Little Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The Mosquito Fire began in Placer County, 4 miles east of Foresthill near Mosquito Ridge Road, CA, and close to Oxbow Reservoir the evening of September 6, 2022, at 6:27 PM PDT and later spread into El Dorado County, CA. The cause is under investigation. The fire started in extreme heat and very low humidity, in an area with drought conditions with exceptionally dry vegetation.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Mosquito Fire started on September 6th, which had all-time record high temperatures in the area set and extremely low humidity dropping into the single digits. Extreme fire behavior was observed due to the very dry humidity and fuels, with the fire developing large plumes that radar indicated extended up to 40,000 feet. In the first few days, the fire saw rapid growth at 5,705 acres by 7 pm PDT on the 7th and 13,705 acres by 8 pm PDT on the 8th. More than 11,000 people were evacuated and 9,000 structures were threatened. The fire included areas in both the Tahoe and Eldorado National Forests. The fire burned a total of 76,788 acres and caused road closures throughout the area. There were 2 firefighters injured during the fire. A total of 78 structures were destroyed and an additional 13 buildings were damaged in the towns of Foresthill, Volcanoville, and Michigan Bar. Fire activity moderate from around September 9 on with cooler onshore flow bringing in higher humidity, with a building smoke inversion further decreasing activity. Periods of moderate to heavy rain from September 18-21 largely halted fire growth. Evacuation orders were lifted on September 21, but the fire was not considered fully contained until October 22.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep trough across the eastern United States helped propel a strong cold front across central North Carolina during the late afternoon into the evening hours of October 17th. The strong dynamics and deep layer shear allowed for the development of a broken band of showers and storms along and ahead of the front. A couple of the storms became severe and produced large hail and damaging wind gusts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Half dollar size hail was reported near the intersection of Hillsborough Road and Britton Drive.

A mulch fire initiated late morning on October 23rd at a compost facility just south of Interstate 470 in far south Kansas City, MO (just west of the Lee's Summit city limit). Smoke from the fire shut down I-470 for a couple hours and an apartment complex was asked to evacuate. The fire was mostly contained by that evening but continued to smolder for days, even briefly re-igniting on October 26th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A fire initiated within a compost pile at Missouri Organic Recycling at 10301 Raytown Road in south Kansas City around 11 AM . This pile was nearly 3 stories tall and consisted of tree limbs, grass clippings, and other yard waste. Weather conditions around ignition time were a temperature of 75, relative humidity of 55 percent, and winds out of the south as 19 knots gusting to 34 knots. Smoke from the fire shut down Interstate 470 for a couple hours. The fire was also able to jump I-470 due to the strong southerly winds and burned an abandoned house, barn, and multiple garages north of I-470.  Residents of View High Lake Apartments were evacuated as a precaution, but the fire was contained before threatening any dwellings. The fire continued to smolder for several days, and even briefly re-ignited on October 26th. Ten fire departments and 4 law enforcement agencies responded to the fire.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed along and south of a stationary front the afternoon of July 14 as an upper level disturbance dropped southwest through the region. Damaging wind gusts and hail occurred with a few of these storms near and just south of the DFW Metroplex.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter reported quarter sized hail near the intersection of Highway 287 and Lone Star Rd in northeast Johnson County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On the afternoon of 10/21, a wildfire burned 10 to 15 acres near Bucker, MO. Weather conditions were favorable for fire ignition and spread that afternoon with very warm temperatures, very low humidity, and strong southwesterly wind gusts. Two firefighters were injured (one critically) fighting the fire.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An illegal outdoor burn started a wild/grass fire at 31000 E Blue Mills Road in Buckner, MO around 2 pm CDT on 10/21. The fire only burned about 15 acres, but 2 firefighters were injured and their brush truck was destroyed battling the fire. One of these firefighters was critically injured and had to be hospitalized.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Significant precipitation deficits in the summer and continuing into the fall led to severe drought developing across portions of north central Missouri by early October and continuing through the end of the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Significant precipitation deficits over the summer months and continuing into fall led to severe drought developing across north central and northeastern Missouri. On October 4th, the drought monitor showed D2 drought building into eastern Adair County, with this expanding further to include most of the southern two thirds of the county by mid October and continuing through the remainder of the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Arctic air masses moved into Ontario, Quebec on January 26th and 28th. These created bitterly cold conditions during the night of January 26th into the morning hours of the 27th. Wind chills were in the 20 to 30 below zero range with actual air temperatures in the 10 to 25 below range. During the morning of January 29th, a powerful Nor'easter was rapidly intensifying southeast of New England that helped advect cold air on brisk north winds across northern VT. Actual air temperatures Saturday morning (29th) were 0 to 10 below zero with wind chills of 20 to 25 below zero.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Bitterly cold wind chills of 20 to 25 below zero late Wednesday night (26th) through mid-morning Thursday (27th) and again late Friday night (28th) into midday Saturday (29th). Actual air temperatures were 10 to 15 below zero on the morning of the 27th and around zero on the morning of the 29th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Warm, moist, and unstable air spread north across North and East Texas, North Louisiana, and extreme Southern Arkansas during the evening through the early morning hours of April 4th-5th, behind a warm front that lifted north through these areas. Meanwhile, an upper trough dug through Western Texas and into the Southern Plains during the afternoon and evening hours of the 4th, enhancing large scale forcing along and ahead of a dry line that developed and spread east across North-central Texas. This resulted in shower and thunderstorm development which rapidly intensified over this area, which spread east into East Texas and Southeast Oklahoma during the late evening hours of the 4th. Given the extent of elevated instability and the strong southerly low level jet in place across Southeast Oklahoma and Southwest Arkansas, these storms became severe as they spread east across these areas, resulting in multiple reports of hail as these storms organized into a quasi-linear convective system (QLCS) which quickly spread across the region through the pre-dawn hours. These storms exited Southwest Arkansas during the overnight hours on the 5th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail fell in the Faircrest community.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An arctic front draped across the VT-Canadian border during the morning of February 3rd and slowly drifted south across VT during the day and evening hours before temporarily stalling along the VT/MA border until the afternoon of February 4th. Light precipitation moved across VT during the morning of February 3rd morning, initially falling as light rain before changing primarily to light snow during the afternoon for much of VT except the southern four counties. ||During the late evening and overnight hours of February 3rd into the midday hours of February 4th, a series of weak low pressure areas moved northeast along the aforementioned boundary as this boundary slowly draped south along the VT/MA border. Moderate to heavy snow at times (>1 inch/hr) moved across much of VT during the night of February 3rd into midday of February 4th. Meanwhile in southern Rutland and southern Windsor counties, especially further south toward the MA border, freezing rain and sleet fell until the early morning hours of the 4th with some icing and ice/snow weighted trees causing some power outages.||Storm total snowfall ranged from 4 to 8 inches across the extreme southern portions of Windsor and Rutland counties where sleet and ice were prevalent as well to 12 to 16 inches elsewhere across central and northern VT.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Total snowfall ranged from 10 to 14 inches with much of this falling in the late evening of February 3rd to around daybreak on February 4th.

Strong to severe thunderstorms developed across west central Arkansas during the late afternoon of the 15th, along a cold front that had become nearly stationary over the area. Additional thunderstorms moved into the area during the evening. The combination of strong instability and moderately strong deep layer wind shear promoted the development of a few supercell thunderstorms. The strongest thunderstorms produced hail up to ping pong ball size and damaging wind gusts.
Scattered thunderstorms developed around portions of Mississippi on August 21st. Some became severe and produced damaging wind gusts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A barn was destroyed by severe downburst winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Several widespread, heavy rain events during October helped ease the drought across much of far eastern Oklahoma during the month. However, the remainder of eastern Oklahoma, especially areas north of I-40 and west of Highway 69, received below average precipitation for the month, much of that area only receiving between 25 and 50 percent of average rainfall amounts. As a result, exceptional drought (D4) conditions expanded across portions of northeastern Oklahoma to include all of Washington, Nowata, and Rogers Counties, as well as portions of Cherokee, Wagoner, Tulsa, Mayes, Ottawa, Craig, and Osage Counties. Exceptional drought (D4) conditions also continued across portions of Pittsburg, McIntosh, Okmulgee, and Okfuskee Counties. Severe (D2) to extreme (D3) drought conditions persisted across the remainder of eastern Oklahoma through the month, although as noted previously, some improvement did occur across far eastern Oklahoma. Monetary damage estimates as a result of the drought were not available.

A strong area of low pressure across the Northern Plains lifted a warm front across the Northland on Memorial Day morning. Showers and storms moved through during the morning hours with the atmosphere recovering during the afternoon hours. A few of the storms were severe during the morning and produced small hail and tree damage. An arc of thunderstorms developed across southwestern Minnesota and adjacent areas of Nebraska, South Dakota and Iowa by the mid-afternoon hours and moved to the northeast and across the Northland for the late afternoon and evening hours. These storms were much stronger and contained very strong winds that produced widespread damage across the region. Additionally, there were a few embedded tornadoes with the storms with the strongest tornadoes producing EF-1 damage in the Deer River and Hinckley areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple trees were reported down with several on power lines.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level disturbance approached the Rockies and provided a strong jet that would move over the Panhandles.  Very warm temperatures across the northern Panhandles allowed for the strong winds aloft to mix down.  Further south winds were still strong and would gust in the 25 to 45 mph range, but would not perform as well as the areas to the north, nor get as warm.  This was due to moisture transport over the area and the cloud cover associated.  Impacts were north of the Romero to Dumas to Beaver line, as these were the areas that managed the least amount of cloud cover.  In these areas winds would be sustained over 40 mph on and off and we would see gusts range from 58 mph to 67 mph.   Dumas was the highest to gust in at 67 MPH.

A surface trough moving from the southeast and south, and an upper low far west of the islands created instability statewide.  These features produced heavy showers and thunderstorms over portions of the state.  Rainfall was particularly intense over parts of Oahu, Kauai, and the Big Island which led to flash flooding.  There were no reports of serious injuries.  The costs of any damages were not available.  This episode is a continuation from the end of December.

A cold front moving through southern Wisconsin was the focus for tornadic development through the lunch hour.  Temperatures and dew points rose enough in the late morning to help fuel the strengthening of the rain along the front.  There were numerous tornadic debris signatures that developed, many of which appeared to be extremely brief which did no damage outside of lofting leaves into the air.  The main tornado for this event was the one that went through West Allis which mainly did tree damage as it came through.  No lightning was observed through this event.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 60 mph wind gust was reported in Hartford.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front moved through eastern Idaho breaking down a long lasting ridtge and bringing very strong wind gusts in the 50 to 60 mph range mainly in the Arco Desert and Upper Snake River Plain.   Blowing dust shut down interstate 15 north of Idaho Falls from exits 128 to 135.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Extensive blowing dust reduced visibility to near zero north of Idaho Falls on interstate 15 and it closed from exit number 128 to 135 at 248 PM MDT and was reopened before midnight.    Wind gusts in the region were extensive in the 50 to 55 mph range with the peak 56 mph at Kettle Butte.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Pre-frontal strong thunderstorms moved offshore of the NE FL Atlantic coast in the mid-afternoon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The St. Augustine C-man station SAUF1 measured wind gust of 43 mph from the WNW.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A meandering frontal zone was across North Central Florida as surface high pressure wedged an axis southward across GA. The onshore gradient between these two features produced gusty winds and enhanced low level isentropic lift near the meandering front which produced periods of heavy rainfall across portions of the coast and NE FL.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A mesonet station measured 3.71 inches of rainfall in 2 hours.

This combined with leaves on tress led to several reports of downed trees and power outages in these areas. Roads also became snow covered for a time with a few accidents reported across the region.
